<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Your tests, while definately showing that magic resistance is an important factor in determining your ability to mez/charm, also do not take into account every factor that I think is involved. I believe that Magic Resist, Difference in level, Spell level used, and Charisma all play heavily in the Mez/Charm equation.<P>Magic resistance: As your tests clearly show (and anyone who has used Tashani can see) a creatures magic resistance is definately a factor in Mez/Charm line.<P>Level difference: Anyone who has walked around naked in Gfay, waiting for a rez from a cleric, and played with charm knows that a level 6 orc centurian can be sucessfuly charmed for 5 to 10 minutes (almost 100% of the time too) with normal magic resistance and no charisma gear on. Did that ever happen when you were level 12? Probably not. but when your about 40 levels higher, they tend to resist alot less.<P>Spell level: Even though spectres don't require 39th level Cajoling wispers to charm, they sure do resist alot less (in my experience) then if you were to use 24th level Beguile.<P>Charisma: In my experience, higher charisma has helped me Charm/Mez borderline Mobs. This what you were trying to test. But your test was a bit skewed. In order to definatively test effects of charisma you need to change your test somewhat.<P>The things in your test that stayed the same: <BR>Difference in level.... you were both level 50.<BR>Spell level: Using allure and dazzle.<P>That leaves changing charima and magic resists. Well, its apparent by your tests  that magic resistance is a deffinate factor. So now just change charima without changing magic resistance, spell level, or Difference in level and without skewing the data by having unrealistically low or high magic resistance.<P>It's the same as me using all my 200+ charisma to conduct a test on a level 2 orc pawn or doing it with base charisma or 100. The difference in level is so unrealistic that I will always get the same results no matter what my charisma (approximately 100% Mez/Charm)<P>To do the test correctly, I suggest you get your charima as high as possible then bring the subjects magic resist down to a level where you are getting 50% Mez/Charm. Then low your charima steadily and look at the results. I speculate that your will see your Mez/Charm resists go way up.<P>I could be wrong of course, but this is the real test I would like to see, and I would actually believe. I'm not about to dump all my charima gear just becuase I have Tashania. In my experience, high charisma has made my enchanter's life much easier than high intellegence. Besides, its hard to imagine them putting in a spell line that raises charima 30+ for no reason other then selling for a higher price.<P><BR>Edit: I forgot to include that I also think PvP numbers may be skewing the data somewhat. Making just about every result in a PvP test highly suspicious. Maybe if someone could find a mob that can be Mezzed approximately 50% of the time, and then lower their own charimsa to check the results? It would be harder to conduct on an unwilling subject, of course, but would probably yield better results.<P>Tatianna<BR>45th Enchantress<BR>Tribunal<p>[This message has been edited by Tatianna (edited 02-02-2000).]
