<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
As someone whose profession has a lot to do with statistical test (financial economics researcher, in case you're curious), I'd like to point out a few things.<P>First of all, I couldn't find any fault with the original methodology. Recall that this is a simple A/B test. First, MR is maxed, test the resist rate. Next, reduce Chr then test again. Compare the result. What that tells you is the effect of Chr when MR is high. Now, MR is reduced and the test is repeated. What it tells you is the effect of Chr when MR is high. What it doesn't tell you though is the potential MR/Chr interaction. It doesn't render the finding invalid. What we know is that holding MR constant, in a PvP situation. Chr has no detectable effects. That's a valid conclusion. How you make of it depends on your prior belief.<P>The only two glaring weaknessess are the sample size and the fact that this is PvP which may be somewhat irrelevant when one considers the implication on PvE situation, which is incidentally more prevalent.<P>To the first weakness, I have this to say. Testing a hypothesis when the null is the truth is more problematic. To elaborate, if Chr is indeed useless, your conclusion will be negative most of the times, and you'll be taking criticism about the test lacks power. It's akin to proving the negative. You can never find enough evidence to unequivocally prove it. Having said that though I admit that 10 sampling is small.<P>To the second weakness, the applicability of the test result depends on some assumptions. To say that PvP and PvE aren't comparable, you must be assuming that somehow Chr is singled out to be treated differently under PvP and PvE situation. For instance, the equation that determines PvP resistance may not contain Chr variable, while the equation that determines PvE resistance may.<P>It's okay to believe thus, but as I said, the conclusion is based on your prior. I don't find it particularly convincing that somehow Verant decides that Chr should have no effect in PvP when it does in PvE.<BR>
</FONT>
