<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The law of averages states that the more often a process is repeated the closer it will come to it's natural state or average. <P>An example of this would be to take a coin and flip it 10 times. Some would assume that you should get 5 Heads and 5 Tails from doing so when this is not always the case. During some tests you could even arrive with a score of 7 Heads and 3 Tails. Is this a violation of the Law of Averages? No. <P>If you take that same coin and flip it 1,000 times you would come up with a figure that is closer to it's average state (in this case 50/50). Although you might end up with figures that weren't exactly (Say for a thousand tests you might see something like 570 Heads and 430 Tails) at the average you WOULD get figures that are closer to what that average is (in this case you are seeing a 57% Heads and 43% Tails rather than the 70/30 split that you got before. <P>It is because of this law that you can not draw ANY conclussions from a test that has such a small sampleing. In order for the tests to be of any use they would need to be (at a minimum in my oppinion) 100 samples and something more along the line of 500 samples would be preferable. <P>Since it is unlikely that any of us are going to take the time and energy to conduct this broad of a test this isssue will probably be debated until the game goes offline but we can not draw any conclussions about CHR's effects with the information we have now.
</FONT>
